+   r5: SAME 74-script menu as r3 (r4 proved that *adding* entries dilutes and
+   regresses -- menu is saturated).  The new lever is PER-ENTRY INPUT: a parallel
+   sed_klee_inputs[] gives each script its own concrete input template, chosen to
+   drive that script's specific match / cycle branches (digits for [0-9], `abc`
+   for [a-c], four short lines for the line-address commands `2,3d` / `0~2d` /
+   `N;P` / `D`, repeats for backrefs, ...).  r3's single shared template
+   "aa.A1\nbbc" drove only a limited set of regexec.c DFA transitions
+   (build_trtable / check_node_accept_bytes / get_subexp are runtime,
+   input-byte-driven); tailoring the input per script reaches more WITHOUT
+   widening the menu.  sed.c publishes the selected input template via the extern
+   `sed_klee_input_tmpl`; utils.c's fork-free reader pins the input to it.
+   Guarded by KLEE_BITCODE so the cov binary never sees the intrinsics. */
+#include <klee/klee.h>
+static const char *const sed_klee_scripts[] = {
+  /* substitutions + flags */
+  "s/a/b/",    "s/a/b/g",   "s/a/b/p",   "s/a/b/2",   "s/a/b/i",
+  "s/./X/g",   "s/a*/X/g",  "s/^/>/",    "s/$/</",    "s/.*/Y/",
